Missing Values
During feature extraction, some features may be NaN (e.g., when a session has too few sensor events).

The training script (SessionOCSVM.load_and_prepare_data) replaces all NaNs with 0 (via np.nan_to_num).

However, the proper Phase 1 cleaning uses median imputation on the combined training data of the dev users, not zero.

For the new LOUO tuning scripts, missing values are handled by fillna(median) inside the data loader.

The consensus is now to impute with median, not zero, to preserve distribution shape.

Data Cleaning Steps (Phase 1)
Load all training CSVs of the 13 development users.

Remove duplicate columns (exact copies).

Drop features with >60% missing values.

Impute remaining missing values with column median.

Drop features with near‑zero variance (var < 1e‑8).

Compute Spearman correlation matrix; for any pair with |ρ| > 0.95, keep the feature with higher variance, drop the other.

Output cleaned_features.csv (list of surviving feature names).
Also saved: removed_missing.csv, removed_low_variance.csv, removed_correlation.csv for audit.

The cleaned feature list is then used by all subsequent ranking phases.

Data Preprocessing
Scaling: Before feeding into OCSVM, features are standardised using StandardScaler fitted only on the user’s own training data (or, during LOUO, on the fold’s training data).

RobustScaler has been discussed as an alternative but not yet implemented in the main pipeline.

No other normalisation (e.g., min‑max) is applied.

Label encoding: In the tuning scripts, label is expected to be 0 (genuine) / 1 (impostor). The LOUO script uses this directly. The main training script normalises to 1/-1.

Train / Validation / Test Split
The project does not use a traditional train/val/test split because of the per‑user nature of the data. Instead:

Per‑user models: Each user gets their own OCSVM. Training data = the genuine sessions of that user. Test data = a held‑out set of that user’s genuine sessions + all their impostor sessions.

Hyperparameter tuning: Uses Leave‑One‑User‑Out (LOUO) on all available users (10 currently). For each fold, the model is trained on the combined genuine sessions of the other 9 users, and tested on the held‑out user’s test set. This gives an unbiased estimate of average TAR/FAR/FRR.

Final model: After finding the best global hyperparameters via LOUO, a model is trained for each user on their own genuine training sessions (as in the main script) and evaluated on their own test set. The reported performance is the average over all users.

No separate validation set exists; the LOUO folds serve as internal validation.

